  "prompt": "What are Audio Codecs?",
  "response": "Audio codecs are algorithms or devices used to compress and decompress digital audio data. They play a crucial role in the transmission, storage, and playback of audio files, ensuring that audio data is efficiently encoded to reduce file size while maintaining quality, and then decoded for playback.\n\nThere are two main types of audio codecs:\n\n1. **Lossy Audio Codecs**: These codecs compress audio data by removing some of the original audio information, which results in a smaller file size but can lead to a loss in audio quality. Common lossy audio codecs include:\n   - MP3 (MPEG-1 Audio Layer III)\n   - AAC (Advanced Audio Coding)\n   - OGG Vorbis\n   - WMA (Windows Media Audio)\n\n2. **Lossless Audio Codecs**: These codecs compress audio data without any loss of quality. The compressed file can be decompressed back to its original state perfectly. Common lossless audio codecs include:\n   - FLAC (Free Lossless Audio Codec)\n   - ALAC (Apple Lossless Audio Codec)\n   - WAV (Waveform Audio File Format, typically uncompressed but can be lossless)\n   - AIFF (Audio Interchange File Format, typically uncompressed but can be lossless)\n\nAudio codecs are essential in various applications, including streaming services, digital music players, video games, and communication systems, helping to balance the need for high-quality audio with efficient data usage.",
